Part 2

By 2022, the *Ummed* brand had moved from yellow paper labels to professional, printed cardboard boxes. The incense sticks were sold in three states, the medical kits were distributed to ninety-two municipal health centers, and the sanitary pads were manufactured in three separate units near Barasat. 

The financial newspapers wrote the numbers: *Seventy-six hundred crore.* 

Vikram didn't read the papers. He still slept in the side room of the Bagbazar house, on the same wooden bench he had claimed when they first arrived from the bypass. 

His clothes were still three faded cotton shirts, washed every morning at the courtyard tap and hung to dry on the line under the neem trees.

Rehman had moved out of the Bagbazar house. He had rented a large apartment in Alipore, with a uniformed security guard at the gate and a silver sedan that was cleaned twice a day by a boy he paid five hundred rupees a month. 

He had traveled to Geneva twice for international NGO conferences. His white kurtas were made of expensive silk now, and his old canvas shoes had been replaced by black leather loafers that had no mud on the soles.

"You should come to the Alipore house, uncle," Rehman had told him during a visit. "It has modern air conditioning. The city summer is bad for your lungs."

"My lungs are used to the neem leaves," Vikram said, looking at the courtyard.

---

The celebration party was held in the lawn of a heritage hotel near the river Hooghly. 

Sarita had returned from New York for the event. She had successfully set up the US fundraising branch, *Punarjeevan International*, which had raised six million dollars in its very first quarter.

The lawn was lit with hundreds of small yellow bulbs hung from the branches of the old mango trees. Seventy people had arrived—three local MLAs, two bank directors, and a group of journalists from the city's business desks. 

Sarita sat in a comfortable cane armchair near the catering tables, her bamboo walking stick leaning against her knee. She looked thinner, but her eyes were bright in the warm light.

"The numbers are huge, Vikram," she said as he stood beside her.

"Yes," Vikram said.

"Rehman did it," she whispered. "He worked eighteen hours a day when I was in New York. He didn't sleep for a week during the Barasat license crisis."

"I know," Vikram said.

A local MLA approached them, holding a glass of apple juice. "Ahuja saab," he said, bowing slightly to Vikram. "Congratulations. What a massive vision. From Odisha to this. Only an Ahuja could have built a service empire this large."

Vikram didn't bother to correct him. He had tried correcting people for five years, but they simply smiled, nodded, and went on writing *Ahuja* in the press reports anyway. 

Rehman was standing three feet away, talking to a bank manager. His glass was whiskey, the ice cubes clicking against the crystal. 

He had heard the MLA's words. He didn't turn around, but his shoulders went rigid under his silk kurta, his hand tightening around the glass until his knuckles went white.

---

The terrace of the heritage hotel was dark. Vikram had gone up there to escape the loud noise of the catering staff clearing plates in the lawn below. 

The river Hooghly was visible between the concrete warehouses, the water black, reflecting the distant yellow lamps of the Howrah bridge.

Rehman's footsteps were heavy on the brick floor of the terrace. He was carrying his whiskey glass, which was now empty.

"They only see you," Rehman said, his voice thick. The smell of alcohol was strong on his breath, mixing with the damp smell of river mud rising from the bank.

"Rehman," Vikram said.

"No," the boy said, walking closer. "Don't say it, uncle. Don't say 'it doesn't matter.' It matters to me."

He looked out at the dark river. "I did the licenses. I did the banking. I did the travel. I lived in cheap hotels that smelled of insecticide for three years to set up the Barasat factory."

He turned to Vikram, his face red in the distant light from the bridge, his eyes wet. 

"And the MLA comes and says: *Only an Ahuja could do this.* What is an Ahuja? A name? A legacy? Just because your father was rich?"

"He didn't know the details, Rehman," Vikram said.

"Nobody knows!" Rehman shouted, his voice echoing off the brick parapet. His glass slipped from his fingers, hitting the floor and cracking with a sharp, dry sound. 

"I am the candle, uncle. I burn myself to give the light. And everyone turns their face to the sun."

He walked to the edge of the terrace, his hands gripping the iron railing. "Is it because of my name? Because I am Rehman? Because my mother converted? Because we had no wealth or house in Odisha?"

Vikram stood behind him. "You built this, Rehman. The board knows. Sarita knows."

"But the world doesn't," the boy said, his voice dropping to a whisper. "I wanted to show them. I wanted to show my mother that I am not the spare. That I can build something bigger than what was taken from us."

He looked back at Vikram. "But I cannot. Not as long as you are standing in the doorway."

He walked past Vikram, his leather loafers making a sharp, clean sound on the brick floor. "I am going to Alipore," he said, without looking back.

Vikram stood alone on the dark terrace. The broken glass of Rehman's whiskey cup was catching the distant light of the bridge. 

The wind from the river was cold. But as he looked at the dark water, the fourteen hundred crore and the seventy-six hundred crore felt like the same thing—a weight he was still carrying, even when he had nothing left in his pockets.

